description.text: This is the cross brace for a quadcopter that I'm working on with a friend.  The holes are made for 3/8" dia carbon fiber tubing that we got off of eBay. A little clip for 1W LEDs. Should be pretty standard dimensions. You normally get these already soldered on a star shaped aluminium plate with solder contacts. But you can also get these without the star patch a lot cheaper. Just keep in mind that they are meant to be soldered to such a star patch to have some cooling, without it they get too hot at full power.
I made this to add some light to my printer, these clips are meant to be tied to the frame using cable ties. Four of those with a little power reduction so they son't run hot produce so much light that the printer illuminates the whole room. The clips are designed that the LEDs have a very tight fit. But with a little pressure they should go in and stay there.

Edit (29.01.2015) Added a few variants.
  • Turned the guide for the cable tie by 90°.
  • Added a version with a cut out shaft for adding small aluminium piece to cool the LED. The aluminium piece should be 2mm thick and 5mm wide and any length you see fit. Would be wise to also put a small smear of heat transmitting paste between the aluminium and the LED. With this you can run the LED at full power without overheating it.
  • Added a version with turned cable tie guide and shaft for aluminium cooler.
    • ( i had to increase the thickness for the versions with shaft for cooler, otherwise the trench would have cut through the cable tie guide, but the whole thing is still very compact)

After having had a jaw operation I have become really addicted to my swiss army knife and especially the toothpick in it. As part of a project that I did recently I designed an asteroidal survey craft called the Emissicius. It will be accompanied by a SoLTeC (Solar Laser Transducer Craft, which flies alongside the ship and beams power over.). The first part of the operation consists of an asteroid survey ship which flies out before the actual mining rig flies out. This ship will also carry a Stradivarius sonic jackhammer, which is an original idea of mine. The front mounted Stradivarius undocks from the mothercraft and flies to the surface where four large screws will embed it into the asteroid. It’s first mission is to find the asteroid’s composition. Once secured it transmits a series of sonic waves through the asteroid by means of a pressurised speaker bag in very close contact with the surface. It works under the same principle as an impactor probe, by firing sonic waves through the asteroid, seismic detectors and microphones can make an internal structure map, showing the entire makeup of the asteroid (similar to sonar), showing the weaker areas, the stronger areas, the internal structure, the topography and all the materials the asteroid is composed of and where they are positioned in the asteroid. The second part of the ship, is the ship’s computers, batteries and instruments bay. This area holds the cameras to look at the asteroid’s surface and also to find flat areas for landing. This area also has a laser, to carve out landing areas, should they be unavailable. They can also be used to vaporise the surface regolith so that spectrometers can see the makeup of the asteroid regolith from above. Also in the instruments bay is a landing craft, that will carry down the microphones to the surface. This drop ship (shown above), is about forty centimetres in height with a radius of the lander base at about 30 centimetres in diameter. This lander goes down to the asteroid and allows the microphones to magnetise and drive around on the surface. The actual rollers themselves which will operate on the surface, will only work on ferrous asteroids. They receive power from one of the nearby SoLTeCs which power the mining operation. Each of these is about the size of an average iPhone, they have two screw like wheels which will rotate to drive it forward, backward and counterrotate to let it turn in 360°. When they are positioned correctly, a pair of pitons will dig into the surface of the asteroid, attaching the rover to the asteroid. When it is dug in, the wheels will demagnetise as not to interfere with the microphone. They have a drop down microphone which (when the rover is in position) will lower down to the surface and listen for the Stradivarius to output it’s sound pulse. Once the microphones are in place, and their screws are down. The Stradivarius will let off a series of sound pulses. These pulses will map the internal structure of the asteroid and find the weak areas in the structure. This process will continue for days until the next part of the process can begin However, since the magnets only work on ferrous asteroids, these microphones can also be dropped as a huge net which is placed on the asteroid as opposed to this rover design.
Notes: I'd orientate it so that the engines are pointed downward and the screws are pointed upward, to save the detail & minimise the need for supports.

The Ouroboros is an ancient symbol of a serpent eating its own tail. It is often said to symbolize the cycle of death and rebirth, but I think it applies just as well to the way new ideas and designs are derived from old ones in a collaborative environment such as Thingiverse. In any case, my girlfriend likes it. Part of this thing's purpose is to show an example of personalizing the flexible bracelet design to a sculpture of your choice. The head of the snake is actually http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1466, simplified in MeshMixer.

This bracelet has a circumference of 17.1cm, so scale the file as necessary for the intended wrist size.  Initial z-height calibration must be quite accurate or else you'll have to trim down the squashed-out bits of the tabs with an exacto knife to make everything fit.  Set "infill begin rotation" to zero in the fill section of SF, so that the fill lines run the length of the bracelet for strength.  
The body of the snake was created from the attached Matlab script (which again, should also work in Octave, provided you download surf2stl from the file exchange).  The OpenSCAD file has a number of parameters that can be tweaked, or you can simply use it as a template for creating your own bracelet.

title: Delta G2S Configuration for Repetier Firmware

description.text:
This isn't a printable thing. It is a starting configuration for running Repetier-Firmware on the Geeetech Delta G2S printer. My printer is working beautifully on this firmware, much smoother than the old Marlin stuff, along with a number of new features. Give it a try. To use:
  • Go to [https://www.repetier.com/firmware/dev/index.php]
  • Upload the enclosed .json file as your "old" configuration.
  • Complete the configuration tool steps, adjusting where needed to match YOUR printer.
  • At the end, choose "Download complete firmware" to retrieve the entire firmware package (.zip file).
  • Compile and upload to your printer as you have done with Marlin.
  • Further configuration changes should always be performed via the online configuration tool. DON'T edit your Configuration.h file directly.
    • Notes:
  • Pay attention to the diagram showing how to measure dimensions of your printer. Some of these may differ slightly from the ones used in Marlin.
  • Extruder offsets are handled entirely within the firmware. You should enter ZERO offsets in your slicer and Repetier-Host configurations.
  • This firmware is under active development. If you happen to download a copy that fails to compile, just try again after a couple of days. Chances are the problem will have been fixed.
    • Disclaimer: I am not associated with Repetier. I'm just a happy user. Update: I'm current recommending use of the "development" version. You can still upload my posted json file as your starting configuration.

Update 15-Oct-2016: I'm changing my MPCNC over to the HicWic universal tool mount so I've added an adapter to allow my laser mount to connect to the HicWic system. If you're using this deign with the HicWic mount then you don't need the conduit clamp. Laser set-up guide on the Vicious1 website, Thanks again Vicious and HicWic for your contributions! http://www.vicious1.com/the-2-8-watt-100-laser/ This is the laser mount I conjured up and is featured on my $100 2.8 watt laser write-up found on the vicious1 website. I wanted something that could be installed or removed in seconds and didn't want to remove my spindle to install it so this what I made up. The connector is a 4pin XLR chassis mount connector and can be found on ebay. The shroud has a channel that can accept a piece of laser shield plexi like that sold by Jtech photonics or just get a pair of tin snips and create a laser shield from a cheapo pair of laser goggles. I cut pieces of 1/4-20 thread rod and glued them to the shroud and the mount to allow a secure and quick height adjustment for the shroud through the meshing of the threads. There are also circular cavities in the shroud for 8mm dia. x 3mm thick neodymium magnets that will hold the shroud in place pretty securely once the threads mesh together.
The tapered dovetail on the mount fits nice and secure in the conduit clamp but there are magnet cavities there too in case you want extra hold. I wasn't planning to share but a couple of people asked so what the hell. Recommend electrical tape around conduit before putting the clamp on so it won't slip. The 55mm laser focus "gage" I use is also posted. Oh, you'll need a 6-32 screw and lock nut for the clamp.

description.text:
Students will work in a group based environment to solve a progression of design challenges relating to the manufacture of objects. Each challenge will build student knowledge of proportions in relation to scaling factor. Beginning with a preselected object, the students measure, sketch, and model the object, both on paper and using Computer Aided Design (CAD) software. Scaling the object is the focus throughout the challenges, with the culmination of printing the scaled object on a 3D printer so they may have a tangible product of their work. Incorporating a CAD program, which is both powerful and approachable, promotes growth in computer skills as well as the underlying skills of problem solving and self directed learning through engagement.
For this MakerEd challenge, an example object has been modeled and uploaded in its various stages. Any number of objects could be used to customize this lesson to the school site, classroom, or student.

Since this is a classroom project with a variable object of design, the tools for design are more important than the object. The way I designed the sample object for this challenge is with the same tool I would expect students to use, as listed in the lesson overview. I used TinkerCAD to design LilBot for two reasons. First is that I wanted to learn the tool myself so that I may assist my students in using it, and second is that it has a low barrier to entry.
I selected a simple sample model for this as a demonstration for the steps overview. The object can be selected by the student or group, and the method be applied.

Making Ratios - Scaling objects challenge Unit: Ratios and Proportional Relationships and or Geometry
Standards: 7.RP.1, 7.RP.3, 7.G.1
Emphasis: 7.G.1 - Relating scale to unit rate to solve real world scale problems Objectives and Overview
Students will work in a group based environment to solve a progression of design challenges relating to the manufacture of objects. Each challenge will build student knowledge of proportions in relation to scaling factor. Beginning with a preselected object, the students measure, sketch, and model the object, both on paper and using Computer Aided Design (CAD) software. Scaling the object is the focus throughout the challenges, with the culmination of printing the scaled object on a 3D printer so they may have a tangible product of their work. Incorporating a CAD program, which is both powerful and approachable, promotes growth in computer skills as well as the underlying skills of problem solving and self directed learning through engagement. For this MakerEd challenge, an example object has been modeled and uploaded in its various stages. Any number of objects could be used to customize this lesson to the school site, classroom, or student. Materials and requirements
-Preselected objects for the students to model. These should be real world but fun objects with simple, yet challenging design features. Fun objects with they can either use or wear when finished are ideal.
-Chromebooks or workstations with access to the Internet.
-Web-based CAD software, such as Tinkercad or OnShape are ideal as they do not require installation on workstations and are free to use. Students can create their own free accounts to store their work as they progress.
-3D Printer in the classroom for students to use.
-An assortment of measuring tools for students to use to measure their objects. Quality measurement tools with scales in metric (mm) are ideal. Speciality measuring tools, such as calipers are helpful as well and will expose students to alternative measuring tools which they may not be familiar with.
-Graph paper for sketching. Quality paper with varying grid scales will allow for greater accuracy and end product.
-Students arranged in groups/teams. Sequence
This is a multi-day progression with a variable number of days and challenges, depending on the level of the class and students. Day 1 - Introduction to 3D printing
A brief history and development of additive design and its uses.
Demonstrate the 3D printer in action - the sight and sound of a 3D printer is unique and will attract student attention!
(Optional) Have ready made fun objects pre-printed for the students to interact with and possibly keep to share. Day 2 - Introduction to design challenge and its phases
The challenge is broken down into set tasks which build upon each other.
Introduce students to the end result, as well as the progression so they have a clear idea of where their work is leading. The exception to this is with an optional task of changing the scale and number of items to be printed (See Optional Task below). Day 3-4 - Object selection and sketching
Example: LilBot Robot
LilBot is a simple robot model that students can customize. It is an example of a simple yet effective object to use for this challenge. See the uploaded model associated with this write up.
Students either select their object or it is assigned to them by the teacher. Students will be more engaged with the challenge if they have the freedom to choose.
Students spend the day sketching their item to the highest level of accuracy possible. All members of the group are working on the same object, so they develop communication and collaboration skills.
Teacher is a facilitator but should refrain from doing the actual measuring.
Students should be encouraged to work together and compare sketches to refine and develop their measuring skills (SMP2)
Once they all have a sketch, a gallery walk or group share out is next so that all groups have a chance to both learn from other groups, as well as offer critique (SMP3) Day 5-6 - Scaling factor challenge
Introduce class to the first challenge: objects need to fit in the “build area” of the 3D printer. This does not have to be the true build area, but rather a portion of it to create the challenge. Possibly divide the build area by the number of groups so they each get their portion.
Show class a 3D rectangular prism representing the build area of the printer. Ideally this is a clear acrylic box that is open on one side so that the students can try to place their objects in the build area (objects should be too big to fit in the box so they are forced to scale down their object).
Students must decide on an appropriate scaling factor for their object and redraw it on graph paper. This can be a real challenge, as they have to apply the scaling factor to each dimension and feature of their object.
Teacher circulates to provide support to students/groups in how to apply a scaling factor.
Gallery walk or presentations of group sketches to promote discussion and peer evaluation/critique (SMP3). Day 7 - Introduction and discovery of CAD software
Chromebooks or computer lab required.
Brief teacher led introduction to either Tinkercad or OnShape (depending on teacher preference and familiarity). Demonstration of what CAD is and some of the basic tools for creating objects.
Student exploration time. Have students just play with the software, without the goal of modeling their object.
Students may begin modeling their object. Day 8 - Object modeling time
Allow students to model their object.
Work as group team to support each other's development.
Teacher facilitates lower skill level students. Day 9 - Optional Task: Multi-part and change of scale
Introduce this challenge as if you were the customer liaison for a company and the students are the engineers.
The customer wants to keep cost down, so they want to make the object smaller so more can be printed in one batch.
Students must re-scale their object so a given number can be printed at one time in the build volume. It would be a good idea to have them build enough so that each group member gets a printed copy when the challenge is complete. Expected Outcomes Students will likely enter this challenge with little to no knowledge of 3D printing and CAD software. The intent of this challenge is to give them an opportunity to explore this field as well as give them a glimpse into the world of engineering and design, all the while applying the concept of scale (7.G.1).
Success in this challenge can me measured in the following ways:
Using appropriate methods of measurement (SMP 5)
Modeling objects with drawings.
Application of scale (7.G.1).
Exposure to Computer Aided Design applications and 3D modeling
Creating a printable part for 3D printing
Working as a creative team to accomplish challenge goals
Analyze and critique the work of others throughout the design process (SMP 3)

This is a free to download only, to sell this shell would be illegal as this was created on an educational license. If you were sold this, report whoever sold it to you. The shell is property of Matthew Schalk and was uploaded for free use only. Assembly:

1/29/2016

Added a RAM Adapter port cover to protect it if put in storage and uploaded some pictures of a final print that I made on my Prusa i3. 1/11/2018
Added a V2 version. This version has screw holes and no text, so that way it can be printed in a way that it can be screwed together. The threading hole is 2mm in diameter, so your screw should be 2.4mm overall. Be sure that they are the correct length beforehand, otherwise you could interfere with the components on the board. I used screws from an old laptop for reference. Disclaimer:

One of the unit choices from one of the factions of a minis wargame I'm working on.  
First time trying to make a humanoid in Tinkercad, using an Artists Manequin Re-tinkered model as a base along with a Primitive Head base. I modified the Head in Sculptristo add hair, and may use Sculptris to get a better detail of clothing for a future version of these models!

Made using Tinkercad and Sculptris, with Blender as the go-between because Sculptris doesn't play well with imported spheres.  
For a model, print a Torso, Head, and Legs (Any of the two, they should all be compatible), a Base, and a Backpack, and you can add Flasks, Ammo, Binos, or Packages to taste!
